<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-948-558  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 948 558.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Nov 9 1989 n1189 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Insecurity breeds company caution.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harvey, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Threats posed by viruses and hackers make computer security a hottopic.andP;  A survey of 42 major computer users reveals that securityrisks come frequently from within the company as increasingnumbers of people have access to computer systems.andP;  Surveyrespondents are also threatened by deliberate sabotage, computerfraud, and espionage, and would like to have new laws designed tohelp them fight computer crime.andP;  Most organizations spend about 2percent of their computer budgets on security, but high-techindustries spend as much as 20 percent.andP;  Several organizationsreport abandoning new business ventures due to computer securityfears.andP;  The problem is recognized as complex and insidious, andcatching computer criminals is probably the most difficult part.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SurveyUnited KingdomComputer CrimesOrganizationsLegal Issues.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>